<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7606&amp;p=76082#p76082"><![CDATA[
<div class="quotetitle">qbradq wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><br />The clones are much cheaper and much more readily available in my area than the real hardware.<br /></div><br />I believe this is the case for most parts of the world. I used to like clones because that's all I had before I could buy a real NES. Now that I have some authentic units, I don't ever touch the clones anymore. Even if it's not easy, you should put some effort into buying the real thing, it really is worth it.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Plus wouldn't support for the clones be a requirement of modern homebrew development?<br /></div><br />I'm not sure... Just like I wouldn't want my games to be played on Nesticle I wouldn't want them to be played on inaccurate clones. As a big fan of accuracy, I'd feel kinda bad about legitimizing these cheap clones as actual NES variations.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent"><br />Does anyone have details or can give a more detailed explanation of this "swapped duty cycles" thing?<br /></div><br />The NES has 4 different configurations for how long the sound waves stay up and how long they stay down within their period (I'm not sure if the terminology is right here, I'm not very good with music stuff). Clones got these ratios inverted: when the waves are supposed to stay up 75% of the time and down 25% of the time, they do the opposite, 25% up and 75% down. Something like that.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=95">tokumaru</a> — Fri Apr 01, 2011 7:09 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
